ntsb3737txt-1-5-5-0-1 The private pilot, who was also a mechanic with an inspection authorization, was landing the airplane from a ferry flight after the airplane had been involved in a previous accident (see ANC99LA155). 
ntsb3737txt-1-5-5-0-2 The pilot/mechanic said that immediately after touchdown, the nose wheel began to vibrate. 
ntsb3737txt-1-5-5-0-3 The nose gear assembly collapsed, and the engine firewall to which the temporary nose gear assembly had been attached, sustained substantial damage. 
ntsb3737txt-1-5-5-0-4 Inspection by an FAA airworthiness inspector revealed that a nose landing gear assembly from an earlier model Cessna 182 had been installed without a shimmy damper, and without provision for connection to the steering bungees. 
ntsb3737txt-1-5-5-0-5 A doubler had been installed on the previously damaged firewall to provide mounting structure for the nose gear assembly. 
ntsb3737txt-1-5-5-0-6 A review of photographs taken at the first accident site revealed that substantial damage to the left wing, left horizontal stabilizer and left elevator (including missing the outboard 4 inches of elevator, and the left elevator tip counterweight), tail cone and empennage, and lower engine cowling existed prior to the ferry flight. 
ntsb3737txt-1-5-5-0-7 The FAA issued a ferry permit for the airplane but did not inspect the airplane, nor verify the extent of damage which existed prior to the flight occurring. 
ntsb3737txt-1-5-5-0-8 The airplane had received its last annual inspection on July 18, 1997, 26 months before the first accident. 
